In short, detail as much as you can about the care of the person. Make it personal so people understand who they are dealing with. 
Be SURE to let the person review and comment/change anything so that everyone is on the same page. 
(9/9)

Include something like a quarter so people know about how large the pills are. If possible (and secure) include a picture of the bottle/label so they can be found quickly (be VERY careful with these, as it can expose sensitive info!)
(8/9)

Make sure it is easy to read, but has the detailed info needed (like medication names -- including technical names -- and exact dosages. Don't say "Pain killers" but instead say "Dilaudid (Hydromorphone) 2mg tablets" and include a picture: 
(7/9) https://t.co/z6yf1gDNbs

Make clear sections: 
• Daily Medications
• Daily Care
• Treatment Schedules
• Other Medications
• Instructions in case of ER visit
• Contact info (include Medical proxy, any home nurse, etc.)
(6/9)

This can be especially important if the person has 'chemo-brain' and can't always recall what is happening, what they have, what they take, etc.  
(5/9)

The more detailed, and more clear, you make this information, the more useful it will be. 

Dr.: What medications are you on?
Them: Scan this QR Code
Dr.: Ahh, great (as they read the complete list of all meds and symptoms/ treatments) 
(4/9)

If you create an on-line resource, give the sick person a QR Code or similar so that they can have Drs and Nurses scan it for all the relevant information in case you can't be there to be the advocate. 
(3/9)

Keep it somewhere where anyone involved in their care has access to it (I made a hidden website) and keep it constantly updated. 

Bonus: include pictures of what each pill looks like, etc, so ANYONE can know what meds to give, and when. 
(2/9)

🧵Pro Tip: If you are part of a group of people caring for a sick family member or friend, create a very detailed document which outlines all the aspects of their illness, all of their medications, etc. 
(1/9)
